menu "breadboard: bb_event_routes"

config BB_EVENT_ROUTES_AUTOREGISTER
    bool "Auto-register /api/events route via bb_init"
    default y
    help
        When enabled, bb_event_routes registers GET /api/events automatically
        via the bb_init regular tier after the HTTP server starts.

config BB_EVENT_ROUTES_MAX_CLIENTS
    int "Max concurrent SSE clients"
    default 2
    range 1 32
    help
        Maximum number of simultaneous /api/events subscribers. Additional
        connections receive 503 {"error":"max_clients"}.

        Default is conservative for tight-heap boards (ESP32-S3 without PSRAM,
        ~30 KB heap budget for idle TLS handshake). Each client consumes ~2.7 KB
        (8*256 B payload buf + 8*24 B queue entry overhead + ~88 B mutex).
        Consumers with more heap can override in sdkconfig.

config BB_EVENT_ROUTES_QUEUE_DEPTH
    int "Per-client event queue depth"
    default 8
    range 4 256
    help
        Events buffered per subscriber. On overflow, the oldest entry is
        dropped and the dropped counter is incremented; the next emitted
        frame's id reflects the gap.

        Default is conservative for tight-heap boards (ESP32-S3 without PSRAM,
        ~30 KB heap budget for idle TLS handshake). With default max_clients=2
        and queue_depth=8, each client consumes ~2.7 KB total. Consumers with
        more heap can override in sdkconfig.

config BB_EVENT_ROUTES_RING_CAPACITY
    int "Per-attached-topic replay ring capacity (non-retained)"
    default 16
    range 1 256
    help
        bb_event_ring depth backing replay-on-connect for each non-retained
        (discrete-event) attached topic.

config BB_EVENT_ROUTES_RETAINED_RING_CAPACITY
    int "Per-attached-topic replay ring capacity (retained)"
    default 1
    range 1 256
    help
        bb_event_ring depth backing replay-on-connect for each retained
        (state) attached topic. A retained topic only ever needs to replay its
        latest value on connect, so the default is 1. On no-PSRAM boards this
        saves ~1 KB of internal heap per retained topic compared to the
        non-retained capacity.

config BB_EVENT_ROUTES_RING_MAX_ENTRY
    int "Per-attached-topic replay payload cap (bytes)"
    default 256
    range 16 4096
    help
        Maximum per-event payload size buffered for replay.

config BB_EVENT_ROUTES_POOL_STATIC
    bool "Permanent static-BSS SSE pool (default: lazy heap-backed instead)"
    default n
    help
        The SSE per-client pool (queue entries + payload buffers, and on
        ESP-IDF the writer task stack + TCB) is always index-addressed —
        client slot i deterministically owns pool bundle i for the pool's
        lifetime (B1-478 PR E; no shared free-list, no per-connect
        malloc/free churn). This knob selects the pool's *backing*:

        n (default) — LAZY HEAP-BACKED (B1-491). The pool arena(s) are
        allocated via a single contiguous heap allocation (SPIRAM-preferred
        on ESP-IDF) on the FIRST SSE client connect, not at boot — a board
        that never gets an SSE client (no dashboard attached) pays ~0
        standing RAM. A failed allocation (fragmented/low heap) fails soft:
        the connection is rejected and retried on the next connect attempt,
        never a crash or unchecked NULL. The heap allocation is never freed
        once created (no idle-reclaim) — the per-client bundle includes a
        live FreeRTOS task stack, and freeing a stack out from under a task
        that has not finished exiting is a use-after-free (see B1-484 /
        PR-E-CRITICAL); one standing allocation for the process lifetime is
        the safe trade, and it still fully avoids permanent BSS.

        y — the pre-B1-491 permanent static-BSS arena: fixed BSS reservation
        carved once at boot, sized by the compile-time Kconfig values below,
        never allocated or freed at runtime. Use this on boards that need a
        fully deterministic, zero-heap SSE pool and can afford the fixed
        ~13.5 KB BSS cost at default MAX_CLIENTS/QUEUE_DEPTH/RING_MAX_ENTRY
        (the tightest no-PSRAM boards, e.g. ESP32-C3, generally cannot).

        Both backings are sized by the compile-time Kconfig values
        (BB_EVENT_ROUTES_MAX_CLIENTS, BB_EVENT_ROUTES_QUEUE_DEPTH,
        BB_EVENT_ROUTES_RING_MAX_ENTRY). If the runtime cfg overrides those
        to larger values, acquire returns BB_ERR_NO_SPACE rather than crash.

        In both modes, the writer task is always created with
        xTaskCreateStatic against the pool's stack+TCB bundle, regardless of
        this setting — static allocation is always available on modern
        ESP-IDF (>= 4.3), so this does not depend on any separate Kconfig.

config BB_EVENT_ROUTES_HEARTBEAT_MS
    int "Idle heartbeat interval (ms)"
    default 15000
    range 1000 600000
    help
        On idle, emit a SSE comment-frame `: ping` every N ms so dead peers
        surface promptly via the chunk write.

config BB_EVENT_ROUTES_MAX_TOPICS
    int "Max attached topics"
    default 8
    range 1 64
    help
        Maximum number of topics that can be attached via
        bb_event_routes_attach().

endmenu
